V于1200年出生在英国維爾爾卡爾內时，他的父亲Robert De Blakeland III42岁，母亲Johanna38岁。他于大约1240年与Beatrice Stuteville在英国英格兰維爾爾卡爾內结婚。他们至少是1个儿子的父母。他去世于1245年之后在他的家乡。"},"hr":{"1200–Aft 1245":"1200.–nakon 1245.","1200–1245":"1200.–1245","1215–1303":"1215–1303","1242–1286":"1242.–1286","1158–1200":"1158–1200.","1162–Female":"1162–preminula","1303":"1303","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1158":"1158","1245":"1245","1200":"1200.","Aft 1245":"nakon 1245.","1242":"1242.","1198":"1198.","1286":"1286","1162":"1162","about 1240":"oko 1240.","Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Calne, Wiltshire, Engleska, United Kingdom","Calne, Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Blakeland, Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England"},"cs":{"1200–Aft 1245":"1200–po 1245","1200–1245":"1200–1245","1215–1303":"1215–1303","1242–1286":"1242–1286","1158–1200":"1158–1200","1162–Female":"1162–Zesnulá","1303":"1303","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1158":"1158","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","Aft 1245":"po 1245","1242":"1242","1198":"1198","1286":"1286","1162":"1162","about 1240":"okolo 1240","Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Calne, Wiltshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Calne, Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Calne, Wiltshire, Anglie","Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, Anglie","Blakeland, Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, Anglie"},"da":{"1200–Aft 1245":"1200–efter 1245","1200–1245":"1200–1245","1215–1303":"1215–1303","1242–1286":"1242–1286","1158–1200":"1158–1200","1162–Female":"1162–Afdød","1303":"1303","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1158":"1158","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","Aft 1245":"efter 1245","1242":"1242","1198":"1198","1286":"1286","1162":"1162","about 1240":"omkring 1240","Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Calne, Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Blakeland, Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England"},"nl":{"1200–Aft 1245":"1200–na 1245","1200–1245":"1200–1245","1215–1303":"1215–1303","1242–1286":"1242–1286","1158–1200":"1158–1200","1162–Female":"1162–Overleden","1303":"1303","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1158":"1158","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","Aft 1245":"na 1245","1242":"1242","1198":"1198","1286":"1286","1162":"1162","about 1240":"circa 1240","Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Calne, Wiltshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Calne, Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Blakeland, Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England"},"en":{"1200–Aft 1245":"1200–after 1245","1200–1245":"1200–1245","1215–1303":"1215–1303","1242–1286":"1242–1286","1158–1200":"1158–1200","1162–Female":"1162–Deceased","1303":"1303","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1158":"1158","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","Aft 1245":"after 1245","1242":"1242","1198":"1198","1286":"1286","1162":"1162","about 1240":"about 1240","Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Calne, Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Blakeland, Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Blakeland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Lawkland (WR Yorks)."],"variants":[{"name":"Lackland","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Durham): topographic name from Lawkland in Yorkshire. The placename derives from Old Norse <i>laukr</i> ‘leek’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":15,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":24,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Richard de Blakeland IV was born in 1200, in Calne, Wiltshire, England, his father, Robert De Blakeland III, was 42 and his mother, Johanna, was 38. He married Beatrice Stuteville about 1240, in Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died after 1245, in his hometown."},"et":{"1200–Aft 1245":"1200–pärast 1245","1200–1245":"1200–1245","1215–1303":"1215–1303","1242–1286":"1242–1286","1158–1200":"1158–1200","1162–Female":"1162–Surnud","1303":"1303","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1158":"1158","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","Aft 1245":"pärast 1245","1242":"1242","1198":"1198","1286":"1286","1162":"1162","about 1240":"umbes 1240","Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Calne, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Calne, Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Blakeland, Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England"},"fi":{"1200–Aft 1245":"1200–1245 jälkeen","1200–1245":"1200–1245","1215–1303":"1215–1303","1242–1286":"1242–1286","1158–1200":"1158–1200","1162–Female":"1162–Kuollut","1303":"1303","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1158":"1158","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","Aft 1245":"1245 jälkeen","1242":"1242","1198":"1198","1286":"1286","1162":"1162","about 1240":"noin 1240","Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Calne, Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Calne, Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Blakeland, Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England"},"fr":{"1200–Aft 1245":"